<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C6CFF87FF71FBECFEEDF28D" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF71FBECFD9DF2DD" blockId="10.[166,627,1135,1162]" box="[166,627,1135,1162]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
<heading id="6F6881EC6C6CFF87FF71FBECFD9DF2DD" box="[166,627,1135,1162]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="F39F4D036C6CFF87FF71FBECFD9DF2DD" authority="(Hubner, [1803])" baseAuthorityName="Hubner" baseAuthorityYear="1803" box="[166,627,1135,1162]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Eucarta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amethystina">
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C6CFF87FF71FBECFE4CF2DD" bold="true" box="[166,418,1135,1162]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">Eucarta amethystina</emphasis>
(Hübner, [1803])
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CFB03FEEDF28D" blockId="10.[166,1225,1183,1498]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FD5CFB03FD31F2ED" box="[651,735,1183,1210]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[170,203,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1232,197,1686]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1232,196,1686]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 31–36. Eggs of Heliothinae: 31–32 — Heliothis maritima; 33–35 — Helicoverpa armigera; eggs of Condicinae: 36 — Eucarta amethystina. Scale bars: 33, 36 — 100 µm. 31, 32, 34–35 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453300" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453300/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 36</figureCitation>
), height 
<quantity id="F3679B656C6CFF87FC99FB03FC5EF2ED" box="[846,944,1183,1210]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="F3679B656C6CFF87FBE2FB03FB26F2ED" box="[1077,1224,1183,1210]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="7.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.7">0.7–0.8 mm</quantity>
(n = 5).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7C85650B6C6CFF87FF0CFB43FF1AF38D" pageId="10" pageNumber="363" type="description">
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CFB43FE04F3CD" blockId="10.[166,1225,1183,1498]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surfaces. Micropylar area represented by rosette and 1 row weakly expressed cells (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FD92FB63FD7AF34D" box="[581,660,1279,1306]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[170,203,1708,1730]" captionTargetBox="[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-8@8.[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 37–42. Eggs of Condicinae: 37–38 — Eucarta amethystina; eggs of Bryophilinae: 39–42 — Cryphia fraudatricula. Scale bars: 39–41 — 100 µm; 37–38, 42 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453306/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 37</figureCitation>
). Rosette with 11–12 long and narrow petalled cells and 4 micropylar opening 
<emphasis id="06EBEA926C6CFF87FDC6FA83FDF2F36E" bold="true" box="[529,540,1311,1337]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">s</emphasis>
. Walls of cells elevated. There are 8 of 15 clearly expressed longitudinal ridges radiate from cells of first row. Longest ridges with high combs (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C6CFF87FBB8FAA3FB52F30D" box="[1135,1212,1343,1370]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[170,203,1708,1730]" captionTargetBox="[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-8@8.[170,1230,188,1685]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 37–42. Eggs of Condicinae: 37–38 — Eucarta amethystina; eggs of Bryophilinae: 39–42 — Cryphia fraudatricula. Scale bars: 39–41 — 100 µm; 37–38, 42 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453306" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453306/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">fig. 38</figureCitation>
). Transverse walls less distinct and narrow than ridges. Aeropyles weakly expressed. Chorion faintly pebbled everywhere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C6CFF87FF0CFA03FF1AF38D" blockId="10.[166,1225,1183,1498]" pageId="10" pageNumber="363">Shape of gnawed holes in eggs. Caterpillar nibbles out large oval opening at lateral part of egg.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
